Assuming that the input array S is sorted. So in Fortran, we need to read the array and process it as sorted. But the original code doesn't sort the array. So perhaps the problem expects the input array to be sorted. So the Fortran code can read the array as is, assuming it's sorted. Next, the Java code has three cases: K=1, N-K !=0 (which is the same as K < N?), and else. Let's see: In Java:

if K ==1:

   find the minimum absolute value in the array.

else if (N-K ! =0):

   then loop through the possible starting indices. Wait, N-K ! =0 is equivalent to K ! = N.

Now, handling input:

In Fortran, to read the array, we can read N and K first, then read N integers into an array S.

In the code:

read(*,*) N, K

allocate(S(N))

read(*,*) S But in Java, the array is 0-based. So in Fortran, the array is 1-based. So when the code uses S[i], in Java it's S[i-1] in Fortran. Wait, no. Wait, the code in Java has:

for (i=0; i<N; i++) S[i] = sc.nextInt(); In Fortran, the array S is 1-based. So when processing the code, the indices are adjusted. So when the code in Java uses S[i], in Fortran it's S(i+1). But in the loop for the subarrays, for example, in Java the code is:

for (int i = 0; i <= N-K; i++) {
   int min = S[i];
   int max = S[i + K -1];
   ...
} In Fortran, if the array is 1-based, then the loop would be i from 1 to (N-K+1), and then min_val is S(i), max_val is S(i + K -1 -1 +1)? Wait, no.
